      <hedline>
        <hl1>Please Go to the Principal's Office</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Helen Feit letter rejects assertion in Sept 3 article that 'newly savvy parents have seized on obscure passages in special-education law to wring additional services for their children'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to your article on a national shortage of school principals (front page, Sept. 3), ''newly savvy parents have seized on obscure passages in special-education law to wring additional services for their children.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to your article on a national shortage of school principals (front page, Sept. 3), ''newly savvy parents have seized on obscure passages in special-education law to wring additional services for their children.''</p>
        <p>But parents are not predators. They are simply trying to provide their children with what they are legally due, often after exhausting struggles with their school districts.</p>
        <p>HELEN FEIT, M.D.  Villanova, Pa., Sept. 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
